Call For Papers: b'\nCALL FOR PAPERS\r===========================================\r2022 IEEE Games, Entertainment, Media Conference (GEM 2022 #56474)\rBridgetown, Barbados\rNovember 27-30, 2022\r Sponsored by IEEE Consumer Technology Society (CTSoc)\r SECOND ROUND SUBMISSIONS NOW BEING ACCEPTED UNTIL AUGUST 10, 2022\r The IEEE CTSoc International Conference on Games, Entertainment & Media (GEM) is for researchers and practitioners in all forms of games, entertainment and media. GEM encompasses all aspects of interactive digital media including digital games, game design, new enabling technologies, interactive entertainment, advanced consumer technology systems, immersive experiences, robotics, novel sensing technologies such as motion capture, haptics, emerging media and arts technologies. Our goal is also to consider the social, political, cultural, and philosophical impacts of applying these technologies for the betterment of humanity. GEM is for researchers and practitioners that seek to integrate technology with art, media and entertainment. Participants are in HCI, Digital Arts, Creative Arts, Humanities, Journalism, Robotics, Cybernetics, Cyberpsychology, AI, VFX and other disciplines. They are united in their interest and enthusiasm for exploring GEM\xe2\x80\x99s areas of interest and the significant uses and impacts these technologies have on our lives. The conference will provide networking opportunities for participants to share research, ideas, designs, advancements and experiences on the state-of-the-art and future direction of consumer technologies related to GEM. GEM 2022 will feature a comprehensive high-quality technical & experiential program dealing with a mix of traditional and contemporary hot topics in paper presentations (lecture and interactive style - as preferred by the presenter), tutorials, workshops, mixed panels and high-profile keynotes.\r Publication in the Conference Proceedings and IEEE Xplore\xc2\xae, requires authors to register under the \xe2\x80\x9cFull\xe2\x80\x9d registration category ONLY. Authors with multiple papers may be allowed to register with a reduced additional paper fee if the same author is presenting all papers (maximum of 3 papers). A select few authors with highest reviews may be invited to submit enhanced journal-quality papers to special issues of peer-reviewed journals (e.g. IEEE Transactions on Consumer Electronics, IEEE Transactions on Games and IEEE Consumer Electronics Magazine). For the details and updates, please email curtisgittens@ieee.org..\r Below are the areas of interest for the conference. Other areas related to GEM will be considered.\r- Serious and Applied Games for Health and Wellness\r- Serious Games for Education\r- Industry Applications for Serious Gaming\r- Ethics & Privacy in Games\r- Game design, development and UX standards\r- Game technologies\r- Machine Learning & AI in Games\r- DEIA in Games\r- Sensing Technologies for Games in Pedagogy and Research\r- Immersive Visualizations and sounds\r- VFX & Pipeline design\r- Deep fakes and Entertainment\r- Ethics & Privacy in Interactive Entertainment\r- Interfaces for VR/AR and Immersive Environments\r- Wearables and Tactile Interfaces\r- Social robots and entertainment\r- New Performance Practices\r- AI in show control and automation\r- Virtual cinematography\r- AI, Big Data and IoT in media consumption and dissemination\r- Dis- and mis-information detection and mitigation\r- Offensive, racist and violent language detection\r- Deep Fakes and media\r- High Dynamic Range theories, technologies and challenges\r- Art design and digital media\r- New media technologies in health, humanities and education\r- Psychosocial impact of new media\r  Key Dates (All submission dates are firm and AOE):\rRound 1 Submission Deadline (New Papers): June 30, 2022\rRound 1 Notification: July 31, 2022\rRound 2 Submission Deadline (New & Resubmitted Papers): August 10, 2022\rRound 2 Notification: September 21, 2022\rFinal Papers Due: October 2, 2022\r  For any inquiries, please contact the Executive Conference Chair Dr. Curtis Gittens (curtisgittens@ieee.org). \n\t'

title: b'CPSIOTSEC 2022'
description: b'3RD Workshop on CPS&IoT Security and Privacy'
Categories: b'security' b'cyber-physical system' b'industrial internet of things' b'internet of things'
Call For Papers: b'\n4TH WORKSHOP ON CPS&IOT SECURITY AND PRIVACY (CPSIOTSEC 2022)\rIn Conjunction with the ACM Conference on Computer and Communications Security (ACM CCS)\rhttps://cpsiotsec2022.github.io/cpsiotsec/\r------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r CALL FOR PAPERS\rSCOPE\rThe Workshop on CPS&IoT Security and Privacy (CPSIoTSec 2022) invites academia, industry, and governmental entities to submit:\r Original research papers on the security and privacy of CPS&IoT\rSystematization of Knowledge (SoK) papers on the security and privacy of CPS&IoT\rDemos (hands-on or videos) of testbeds/experiences of CPS&IoT security and privacy research\rWe seek submissions from multiple interdisciplinary backgrounds tackling security and privacy issues in CPS&IoT, including but not limited to:\r Mathematical foundations for secure CPS/IoT\rControl-theoretic approaches\rHigh assurance security architectures\rSecurity and resilience metrics\rMetrics and risk assessment approaches\rIdentity and access management\rPrivacy and trust\rNetwork security\rGame theory applied to CPS/IoT security\rHuman factors, humans in the loop, and usable security\rUnderstanding dependencies among security, reliability and safety in CPS/IoT\rEconomics of security and privacy\rIntrusion and anomaly detection\rModel-based security systems engineering\rSensor and actuator attacks\rCPS/IoT malware analysis\rCPS/IoT firmware analysis\rHardware-assisted CPS/IoT security\rAlso of interest will be papers that can point the research community to new research directions, and those that can set research agendas and priorities in CPS/IoT security and privacy. There will be a best paper and best presentation award.\r New Process for Selecting the Best Paper Award: Following the success of the 2021 process and in the interest of increasing transparency, the PC will select upto 3 top-rated papers based on reviews and place them in a single session. Then the audience will vote on what they think should be the best paper after viewing the presentations.\r------------------------------\r SUBMISSION INSTRUCTIONS\rSubmissions include long papers (12 pages), short papers (6 pages), or 1-page abstracts:\r Long papers include a) Original research on a CPS/IoT security and privacy topic, b) Systematization of Knowledge of CPS/IoT security and privacy;\rShort papers include original work-in-progress research on a CPS/IoT security and privacy topic;\r 1-page abstracts include demos/interesting findings/insights on CPS/IoT security and privacy, which will be accompanied by a hands-on demo during the workshop.\r Submitted papers can be up to 12 or 6 pages excluding appendices and references. Submissions must use the ACM SIG Proceedings Templates, with a simpler version here: https://github.com/acmccs/format. Only PDF files will be accepted. Accepted papers will be published by the ACM Press and/or the ACM Digital Library. Submissions must not substantially overlap with papers that have been published or that are simultaneously submitted to a journal or a conference with proceedings. Each accepted paper must be presented by a registered author. Submissions not meeting these guidelines risk immediate rejection. For questions about these policies, please contact the chairs.\r------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r IMPORTANT DATES\rSubmission Deadline: June 25, 2022 (23:59 Anywhere on Earth time)\rNotification of Acceptance/Rejection: 18 August, 2022\rCamera Ready Papers Due: (hard deadline): September 5, 2022\r------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r ORGANIZING COMMITTEE\r Program Committee Chairs:\rCristina Alcaraz, University of Malaga, Spain\rEarlence Fernandes, University of Wisconsin-Madison, USA\n\t'

Call For Papers: b"\nICAIE2023-2023 3rd International Conference on Artificial Intelligence in Education-Ei Compendex and Scopus\r \xe2\x98\x85 Full name: 2023 3rd International Conference on Artificial Intelligence in Education (ICAIE 2023)\r\xe2\x98\x85 Abbreviation: ICAIE 2023\r\xe2\x98\x85 Website: http://www.icaie.org/\r\xe2\x98\x85 Date: March 16-18, 2023\r\xe2\x98\x85 Held in: Chongqing, China\r ICAIE 2023, 2023 3rd International Conference on Artificial Intelligence in Education, will be held in Chongqing, China during March 16-18, 2023. It's the third year of ICAIE conference, but it will witness the development of the field in artificial intelligence in education. ICAIE will keep working on itself as an event whose aim is to provide this chance and platform for the researchers from academia, industry, and government institutions to exchange and present the novel research on artificial intelligence in education.\r The conference is an annual event held every year to make it an ideal platform for people to share views and experiences in artificial intelligence in education and related areas. The primary goal of the conference is to promote research and developmental activities in artificial intelligence in education and another goal is to promote scientific information interchange between researchers, developers, engineers, students, and practitioners working all around the world.\r - Call for Papers - For more topics, please visit at: http://www.icaie.org/cfp.html\rTopics of interest for submission include, but are not limited to:\r- Basic theory and applied technology of artificial intelligence\rMachine Learning Processing\rMachine Perception and Virtual Reality\rNatural Language Processing and Understanding\rNeural Network and Deep Learning\r - Artificial intelligence and education\rArtificial intelligence algorithms in education\rArtificial neural networks in education\rEducational robotics\rKnowledge Science and Knowledge Engineering\r - Publication -\rSubmitted papers will be peer-reviewed by the technical program committees. Accepted and presented papers in ICAIE 2023 will be published in the Conference Proceedings, which will be indexed by Ei Compendex and Scopus.\r  - Submission -\r1. The official language is English. The submitted paper should be no less than 4 full pages and prepared carefully according to the conference template.\r2. Abstract submission is acceptable but it will be accepted for presentation only.\r * Welcome to submit the paper or abstract by Electronic Submission System:\rhttps://www.zmeeting.org/submission/icaie2023\rMore details about submission, please visit at http://www.icaie.org/sub.html\r - Conference Program -\rMarch 16, 2023 | Sign in and Collect Conference Materials & Online Zoom Test\rMarch 17, 2023 | Opening Ceremony & Keynote Speech & Parallel Sessions\rMarch 18, 2023 | Online Parallel Sessions\r - Contact -\rConference Secretary: Ms. Sylvia\rEmail: icaie_conf@163.com\rTel: +86-180 3055 9376\r \n"

Full paper should be at least full 4 pages and at most 12 pages under the format.\r More detail about submission, please visit at http://www.iceit.org/sub.html\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Conference Schedule\xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85\rDay 1, March 16, 2023 - 10:00 \xe2\x80\x93 17:00: Registration,collecting conference materials \rDay 2, March 17, 2023 - 09:00 \xe2\x80\x93 18:00: Opening Remark & Keynote Speeches & Parallel Sessions\rDay 3, March 18, 2023 - 09:00 \xe2\x80\x93 17:00: Parallel Sessions\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Conference Venue\xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85\rChongqing is the largest municipality in southwest China. Call For Papers: b'\n*ICMAI 2023-Mathematics and Artificial Intelligence Conference - SCI Journal / Scopus & Ei Compendex Index\r \xe2\x98\x85Full name:  2023 8th International Conference on Mathematics and Artificial Intelligence (ICMAI 2023)--SCI\r\xe2\x98\x85Abbreviation: ICMAI 2023\r\xe2\x98\x85Website\xef\xbc\x9ahttp://www.icmai.org/\r\xe2\x98\x85Time\xef\xbc\x9aApril 7-9, 2023\r\xe2\x98\x85Place\xef\xbc\x9aChongqing, China\r  2023 8th International Conference on Mathematics and Artificial Intelligence (ICMAI 2023) will be held during April 7-9, 2023 in Chongqing, China.\rICMAI 2023 welcomes professors, researchers, scholars and industrial pioneers all over the world. It is the premier forum for the presentation and exchange of past experiences and new advances and research results in the field of theoretical and industrial experience. The conference welcomes contributions which promote the exchange of ideas and rational discourse between educators and researchers.\rIt is hoped to influence the spawning of new areas of applied mathematics and the strengthening of the scientific underpinnings of Artificial Intelligence. ICMAI 2023 is aimed at: applied logicians, algorithms and complexity researchers, Artificial Intelligence theorists and applications specialists using mathematical methods. \r \xe2\x98\x85Call for paper\xe2\x98\x85\rTopic about: \rMathematical Foundations \rMathematics, general\rArtificial Intelligence (incl. Robotics)\rAI and Digital Entertainment \rMachine Consciousness \rMachine Learning\rSoft and Evolutionary Computing \rVision and Perception \r For details about topics, please visit at http://www.icmai.org/cfp.html\r \xe2\x98\x85 Publication\rSubmitted paper will be peer reviewed by conference committees, and accepted papers will be included into ICMAI 2023 Conference Proceedings, which will be published in the International Conference Proceedings Series and will be archived in the Online Digital Library, and indexed by Ei Compendex and Scopus and submitted to be reviewed by Thomson Reuters Conference Proceedings Citation Index (ISI Web of Science) \rMore details about publication history, please visit: http://www.icmai.org/history.html\r *Journal Recommendation\r - Journal Recommended: Mathematics (ISSN 2227-7390) is a peer-reviewed open access journal which provides an advanced forum for studies related to mathematics, and is published semimonthly online by MDPI. \rIndexed in the Science Citation Indexed Expanded - SCIE (Web of Science) from Vol. 4 (2016) and Scopus. / Impact Factor: 1.747 (2019)\r - Journal Recommended: Axioms (ISSN 2075-1680) is an international peer-reviewed open access journal of mathematics, mathematical logic and mathematical physics, published quarterly online by MDPI\xef\xbc\x88https://www.mdpi.com/journal/axioms\xef\xbc\x89. It is indexed in SCIE (Web of Science) and Scopus (CiteScore 1.70).\r - Journal Publication: IJSSC - International Journal of Space-Based and Situated Computing\rSpecial Issue on AI-based Situated Services for Smart Cities\r \xe2\x98\x85Submission\xe2\x98\x85\rA. Full Paper (for Presentation and Publication) \rRegular paper is required to have at least 8 full pages including tables, figures and references. A paper is usually no more than 20 pages.\rAccepted full paper will be invited to give the oral presentation at the conference and be publsihed into conference proceedings.\r B. Abstract (Presentation only)\rAccepted abstract will be invited to give the oral presentation at the conference, the presentation will not be published.\r For submission, please upload it to the Electronic Submission System (.pdf)\rhttps://www.zmeeting.org/submission/icmai2023\rSubmission template: http://www.icmai.org/acm_template.docx\rMore detail about submission, please visit: http://www.icmai.org/sub.html\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Conference Schedule\xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85\rApril 7, 2023 | Day 1\r 10:00-16:00 | Sign in and Collect Conference Materials & Online Zoom Test\r Participants are supposed to sign in at the conference venue and collect all the conference materials at the registration counter on this day.\rApril 8, 2023 | Day 2\r  9:00-12:00, Opening Ceremony & Keynote Speeches\r 13:30-18:00, Parallel Sessions ( Oral Presentation )\rApril 9, 2023 | Day 3 - Online Activity\r Online Parallel Sessions\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Chongqing \rChongqing is the largest municipality in southwest China. It is a modern port city on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River at the confluence of the Yangtze and Jialing Rivers. Chongqing is famous for its hot Sichuan cuisine and world-famous hot pot. Various brands of hot pot restaurants can be found throughout the city. The food is delicious even in very small restaurants. Street vendors as well as restaurants feature exciting spicy delicacies for the gourmets. Bayi Food Street in the city center is the best place to taste the spicy local snacks.\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Contact:\rMs. Gretchen Liu (Conference Secretary)\rE-mail: icmai@young.ac.cn \rTel: +86-182-1565-4293\r\n'

You can be encouraged by the fact that the excellent presentation award will be granted. The Organizing Committee of CETA 2023 invites researchers, practitioners and students worldwide to submit the outcomes of their research for consideration to be presented at the conference. Call For Papers: b'\nGiven the huge success of the previous conferences and the strong interest in Nursing 2022, we look forward to welcoming you at our \xe2\x80\x9c3rd Edition of Singapore Nursing Research Conference\xe2\x80\x9d scheduled during March 16-18, 2023 at Singapore. \r Considering the current unprecedented challenges, we have chosen a hybrid format with on-site as well as online editions\xe2\x80\xaffor this conference. \r The congress will be centred around the theme \xe2\x80\x9cExploring Challenges in Nursing Research: The Unsung Frontline Warriors\xe2\x80\x99 Field\xe2\x80\x9d. \r The limits of the global health system have become evident, and socioeconomic determinants have never prioritized their influence. Today, nurses are more than ever needed to combat\xe2\x80\xafthe worldwide pandemic. It is now the time to initiate a\xe2\x80\xafdialogue, in order to improve cultural competence, coherence and equality of healthcare for all individuals, in this vital area of study. 4th International Conference on Blockchain and Internet of Things (BIoT 2023)

March 18 ~ 19, 2023, Vienna, Austria

Scope & Topics

4th International Conference on Blockchain and Internet of Things (BIoT 2023) will provide an excellent international forum for sharing knowledge and results in theory, methodology and applications of Blockchain and Internet of Things. The Conference looks for significant contributions to all major fields of the Blockchain and Internet of Things in theoretical and practical aspects.

Authors are solicited to contribute to the conference by submitting articles that illustrate research results, projects, surveying works and industrial experiences that describe significant advances in the areas of Blockchain and Internet of Things.

Topics of interest include, but are not limited to, the following

  • Block Chain issues and trends\r
  • Blockchain Attacks on Existing Systems\r
  • Blockchain Consensus Algorithms\r
  • Blockchain Foundations\r
  • Blockchain New Design\r
  • Blockchain Privacy\r
  • Blockchain Scalability\r
  • Blockchain-based security for the IoT\r
  • IoT Connectivity and Networking\r
  • Electronics and Signal processing for IoT\r
  • IoT Experimental Results and Deployment Scenarios\r
  • IoT Applications and Services\r
  • IoT Security and Privacy\r
  • IoT-enabled Innovation and Entrepreneurship

Paper Submission

Authors are invited to submit papers through the conference Submission System by October 20, 2022 . Submissions must be original and should not have been published previously or be under consideration for publication while being evaluated for this conference. The proceedings of the conference will be published by Computer Science Conference Proceedings in Computer Science & Information Technology (CS & IT) series (Confirmed).

Selected papers from BIoT 2023, after further revisions, will be published in the special issue of the following journals.

  • International Journal of Network Security & Its Applications (IJNSA) \xe2\x80\x93 ERA, WJCI Indexed
  • Machine Learning and Applications: An International Journal (MLAIJ)
  • International Journal on Cryptography and Information Security (IJCIS)
  • International Journal of Security, Privacy and Trust Management (IJSPTM)
  • International Journal of Ubiquitous Computing (IJU)
  • International Journal on Web Service Computing (IJWSC)
  • International Journal of Ambient Systems and Applications (IJASA)
  • International Journal of Grid Computing & Applications (IJGCA)
  • Information Technology in Industry (ITII)

Important Dates

Submission Deadline: October 20, 2022
Authors Notification: December 20, 2022
Final Manuscript Due: December 28, 2022
'

title: b'SS-ICONIP 2022'
description: b'ICONIP Special Session on Advances in Deep Learning for Biometrics and Forensics'
Categories: b'biometrics' b'forensics' b'artificial intelligence' b'deep learning'
Call For Papers: b'\nSpecial Session on Advances in Deep Learning for Biometrics and Forensics\r The 29th International Conference on Neural Information Processing (ICONIP 2022)\rNovember 22-26, 2022, New Delhi, India (hybrid mode)\r Scope and Aim\r The biometric is a growing technology due to the needs of the society, companies and governments for recognition, security and privacy concerns. It has also become a growing research area that offers greater security and convenience solutions for various applications in biometrics and forensics areas.\r Methods and algorithms from data science are widely explored and used to address several problems in many fields such as biometrics and forensics. In this context, the advances in artificial intelligence, in particular in feature engineering and deep learning, have allowed to resolve various complex problems related to recognition, detection, control, security, forensic identification, etc.\r Indeed, most of biometric systems are based on a typical representation, including biometric data preprocessing, feature extraction, and classification parts. Deep learning offers an end-to-end learning paradigm allowing to unify these parts. It has been shown to be a promising and powerful alternative to conventional approaches based on machine learning.\r This special session aims to bring together researchers, scientists and industry professionals interested in biometrics and forensic, to present and discuss their recent advanced algorithms and methods in deep learning for biometrics and its applications.\r Topics\r The main topics that are of interest to this special session include, but are not limited to, the following:\r     - Deep learning for biometrics and/or forensics\r    - Biometric recognition (authentication and identification)\r    - Physiological and behavioral biometrics (e.g., fingerprint, palmprint, palm vein, face, iris, ear, gait, voice, etc.)\r    - Soft biometrics\r    - Multimodal biometrics\r    - Big Data challenges in biometrics\r    - Attacks to biometric systems\r    - Security and privacy in biometrics\r    - Forensic identification\r    - Emerging biometrics\r     - Related applications\r Important Dates\r     - Paper submission deadline: June 15, 2022\r    - Paper acceptance notification: August 15, 2022\r    - Conference: November 22-26, 2022 \xe2\x80\x93 New Delhi, India\r Submission Guidelines\r Papers submitted to this Special Session are reviewed according to the same rules as the submissions to the regular sessions of ICONIP 2022. Authors who submit papers to this session are invited to mention it in the form during the submission. Submissions to regular and special sessions follow identical format, instructions, deadlines and procedures of the other papers. Click here to information paper submission: https://www.iconip2022.apnns.org/camara_ready_submission.php Please, for further information and news refer to the ICONIP website: https://www.iconip2022.apnns.org\r Organizers\r Larbi Boubchir, Full Professor, LIASD research Lab., University of Paris 8, France (contact: larbi.boubchir@univ-paris8.fr) \r Boubaker Daachi, Full Professor, LIASD research Lab., University of Paris 8, France \n\t'

Call For Papers: b'\nCall for papers for COGALEX-VII\r \xe2\x80\x9cThe 7th International Workshop on Cognitive Aspects of the Lexicon\xe2\x80\x9d\r https://sites.google.com/view/cogalexvii2022/home\r co-located with AACL-IJCNLP 2022\rhttps://www.aacl2022.org/home\r Taipei, Taiwan\r Submission Deadline: 25-Aug-2022\rWorkshop date : Date: 20-Nov-2022  \r Key words: Dictionary, (Mental)Lexicon, Brain, Cognition, Neuroscience, Computational Linguistics; Corpus Linguistics, Complex graphs, Navigation\r Meeting Description:\r COGALEX is a workshop devoted to the cognitive aspects of the lexicon. While in the past, it has always been co-located with COLING, this time it will be hosted by AACL-IJCNLP 2022, at the NTUH International Convention Center, Taipei, Taiwan (https://www.aacl2022.org/home). The accepted papers will be published as proceedings appearing in the ACL anthology.\r The goal of COGALEX is to provide a snapshot of the current state of the art in the different disciplines \xe2\x80\x94lexicography, psycholinguistics, neuroscience\xe2\x80\x94 dealing words, their organization (lexicon) and usage (for example: navigation in a hybrid conceptual-lexical resource; word production and analysis). The approach being deliberately cross-disciplinary.\r In sum, we solicit original and unpublished work related to the cognitive aspects of the lexicon. For details, see: https://sites.google.com/view/cogalexvii2022/home\r Short papers can be up to 4 pages in length and long papers up to 8 pages. Both submission formats can have an unlimited number of pages for references. All submissions must follow the ACL stylesheet. We don\xe2\x80\x99t accept submissions that consist only of an abstract.\r The submissions must be anonymous and they will be peer-reviewed by our program committee. The peer review is double blinded. Papers must be submitted via SoftConf by August 25, 2022.\r Submission page: https://softconf.com/aacl2022/CogALex-VII/user/scmd.cgi?scmd=submitPaperCustom&pageid=0\r At least one of the authors of an accepted paper must register for the main conference and present the paper. Accepted papers (short and long) will be published in the workshop proceedings that will appear in the ACL Anthology. Accepted papers will also be given an additional page to address the reviewers\xe2\x80\x99 comments. The length of a camera-ready submission can then be 4 pages for a short paper and 8 for a long paper with an unlimited number of pages for references.\r We consider to invite the authors of the accepted papers to submit an extended version of their workshop paper for a special issue.\r Important dates\r-     Paper submission (full and short): August 25, 2022\r-     Notification of acceptance: September 25, 2022\r-     Camera ready deadline: October 10, 2022\r-     Workshop: November 20, 2022\r Workshop organizers ;\r -      Michael Zock (CNRS, LIS, Aix-Marseille University, Marseille, France)\r-      Emmanuele Chersoni (The Hong Kong Polytechnic University, Hong Kong, China)\r-      Yu-Yin Hsu (The Hong Kong Polytechnic University, Hong Kong, China)\r-      Enrico Santus (Bayer, Whippany, NJ, 07981, USA)\r For specific requests or information\r Please send an e-mail to  cogalex2022@gmail.com,  or to\rMichael Zock (michael.zock@lis-lab.fr), Emmanuele Chersoni (emmanuelechersoni@gmail.com)\r \n'

title: b'PDSW 2022'
description: b'The 7th International Parallel Data Systems Workshop'
Call For Papers: b"\n=======================================================================================\r\xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 Call for papers: PDSW\xe2\x80\x9922\r\xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 The 7th International Parallel Data Systems Workshop\r\xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0http://www.pdsw.org\r\xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 November 14, 2022 \xc2\xa01:30 PM - 5:00 PM (CST)\r\xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 Held in conjunction with SC22, DALLAS, TX\r\xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 In cooperation with: IEEE Computer Society\r=======================================================================================\r We are pleased to announce the 7th International Parallel Data Systems Workshop (PDSW\xe2\x80\x9922). PDSW'22 will be hosted in conjunction with SC22: The International Conference for High Performance Computing, Networking, Storage and Analysis.\r Efficient data storage and data management are crucial to scientific productivity in both traditional simulation-oriented HPC environments and Big Data analysis environments. This issue is further exacerbated by the growing volume of experimental and observational data, the widening gap between the performance of computational hardware and storage hardware, and the emergence of new data-driven algorithms in machine learning. The goal of this workshop is to facilitate research that addresses the most critical challenges in scientific data storage and data processing. PDSW will continue to build on the successful tradition established by its predecessor workshops: the Petascale Data Storage Workshop (PDSW, 2006-2015) and the Data Intensive Scalable Computing Systems (DISCS 2012-2015) workshop. These workshops were successfully combined in 2016, and the resulting joint workshop has attracted up to 38 full paper submissions and 140 attendees per year from 2016 to 2021. \r We encourage the community to submit original manuscripts that:\r- introduce and evaluate novel algorithms or architectures,\r- inform the community of important scientific case studies or workloads, or\r- validate the reproducibility of previously published work\r Special attention will be given to issues in which community collaboration is crucial for problem identification, workload capture, solution interoperability, standardization, and shared tools.  We also strongly encourage papers to share complete experimental environment information (software version numbers, benchmark configurations, etc.) to facilitate collaboration. \r Topics of interest include the following: \r- Scalable architectures for distributed data storage, archival, and virtualization \r- The application of new data processing models and algorithms towards scientific computing and analysis \r- Performance benchmarking, resource management, and workload studies\r- Enabling cloud and container-based models for scientific data analysis \r- Techniques for data integrity, availability, reliability, and fault tolerance \r- Programming models and big data frameworks for data intensive computing\r- Hybrid cloud/on-premise data processing\r- Cloud-specific data storage and transit costs and opportunities \r- Programmability of storage systems \r- Data filtering/compressing/reduction techniques \r- Parallel file systems, metadata management, and complex data management\r- Integrating computation into the memory and storage hierarchy to facilitate in-situ and in-transit data processing \r- Alternative data storage models, including object stores and key-value stores \r- Productivity tools for data intensive computing, data mining, and knowledge discovery\r- Tools and techniques for managing data movement among compute and data intensive components \r- Cross-cloud data management \r- Storage system optimization and data analytics with machine learning\r- Innovative techniques and performance evaluation for new memory and storage systems\r   Regular Paper Submissions \r-------------------------------------- \rAll papers will be evaluated by a competitive peer review process under the supervision of the workshop program committee. Selected papers and associated talk slides will be made available on the workshop web site. The papers will also be published by the IEEE Computer Society.\r Authors of regular papers are strongly encouraged to submit Artifact Description (AD) Appendices that can help to reproduce and validate their experimental results. While the inclusion of the AD Appendices is optional for PDSW\xe2\x80\x9922, submissions that are accompanied by AD Appendices will be given favorable consideration for the PDSW Best Paper award. \r PDSW\xe2\x80\x9922 follows the SC22 Reproducibility Initiative. For Artifact Description (AD) Appendices, we will use the format of the SC22 for PDSW'22 submissions. The AD should include a field for one or more links to data (zenodo, figshare, etc.) and code (github, gitlab, bitbucket, etc.) repositories. For the Artifacts that will be placed in the code repository, we encourage authors to follow the guidelines of SC22 on how to structure the artifact, as it will make it easier to the reviewing committee and readers of the paper in the future.\r Submit a not previously published paper as a PDF file, indicate authors and affiliations. Papers must be up to 5 pages, not less than 10 point font and not including references and optional reproducibility appendices. Papers must use the IEEE conference paper template available at: https://www.ieee.org/conferences/publishing/templates.html\r  Work-in-progress (WIP) Submissions\r--------------------------------------------------\rThere will be a WIP session where presenters provide brief 5-minute talks (TBD) on their on-going work, with fresh problems/solutions. WIP content is typically material that may not be mature or complete enough for a full paper submission and will not be included in the proceedings. A one-page abstract is required.\r  Important Dates\r----------------------\rRegular Papers and Reproducibility Study Papers:\rSubmissions due: Aug. 13, 2022, 11:59 PM AoE\rPaper Notification: \xc2\xa0 Sep. 9, 2022\rCamera ready due: \xc2\xa0Sep. 30, 2022, 11:59 PM AoE\r Work in Progress (WIP):\rSubmissions due: \xc2\xa0Sep. 16, 2022, 11:59PM AoE\rWIP Notification: \xc2\xa0On or before Sep. 23, 2022\r  Workshop Organizers\r------------------------------\rGeneral Chair\r- Kento Sato, RIKEN R-CCS, Japan\r Program Co-Chairs\r- Amelie Chi Zhou, Shenzhen University, China \xc2\xa0\r- Bing Xie, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, USA \xc2\xa0\r Publicity Chair\r- Jean Luca Bez, Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, USA\r Web and Proceedings Chair\r- Joan Digney, Carnegie Mellon University\n\t"

title: b'CARDIS  2022'
description: b'21st Smart Card Research and Advanced Application Conference'
Categories: b'security' b'hardware' b'cryptography' b'embedded systems'
Call For Papers: b'\nCARDIS has been the venue for security experts from industry and academia to exchange on\rsecurity of smart cards and related applications since 1994. Smart cards play an increasingly\rimportant role in our day-to-day life through their use in banking cards, SIM cards, electronic\rpassports, and IoT devices. It is thus naturally of utmost importance to understand their security\rfeatures and to develop sound protocols and countermeasures while keeping reasonable\rperformance. In this respect, CARDIS aims to gather security experts from industry, academia, and\rstandardization bodies to make steps forward in the field of embedded security.\rThe 21st edition of CARDIS is organized by the Centre for Cyber Security and Privacy of the\rUniversity of Birmingham, UK. CARDIS 2022 will be accompanied by a one-day Fall School event,\rwith more details to be announced.\n\t'

Call For Papers: b'\nWe would like to enthusiastically invite scholars and experts to submit proposals for a chapter to be included in a forthcoming book titled, \xe2\x80\x9cGovernment Response to Disruptive Innovation: Perspectives and Examinations.\xe2\x80\x9d\rSpecifically, we would like to solicit proposals touching on the following themes:\r1. Theoretical framework of disruptive technologies and government responses\r2. Innovations in food systems\r3. Autonomous vehicles\r4. Government use of technology for surveillance and the impact on privacy\r5. Privacy, speech, technology, and the private sphere (workplace surveillance, space tourism, right to repair, etc.)\r6. The use of technology to reduce inequality (my chapter on AI and legal services will fit here.)\r7. Digital interactions between citizens and governments: improving government services\r8. Education\r Please visit https://www.igi-global.com/publish/call-for-papers/call-details/5919 for more details regarding this publication and to submit your work. You can also find detailed manuscript formatting and submission guidelines at http://www.igi-global.com/publish/contributor-resources/before-you-write/. If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to contact me. Thank you very much for your consideration of this invitation, and I hope to hear from you by May 25, the proposal submission deadline!\r Best wishes,\r James R. Masterson\rCo-Editor\rGovernment Response to Disruptive Innovation: Perspectives and Examinations\rAssociate Professor of Political Science\rMPA Director\rMorehead State University\r\n'

title: b'COCOLE 2022'

Call For Papers: b"\nThe 1st International Conference on Computing, Communication and Learning (COCOLE)-2022 will be organized by National Institute of Technology, Warangal, Telangana, India during Sep 29th - Oct 01st, 2022.\r COCOLE conference series is a global platform for computer science researchers to exchange research results and ideas on the foundations and applications of Computing, Communication and Learning. These technologies are increasingly relevant to individuals and organizations who engage in the production, processing and dissemination of knowledge.\r Prospective authors are invited to submit manuscripts reporting original unpublished research and recent developments in the topics related to the conference. These technologies are changing constantly as a result of the large research and technical effort being undertaken in both universities and businesses. The exchange of ideas between scientists and technicians from both academic and business areas is essential to facilitate the development of systems that meet the demands of today's society. The technology transfer in this field is still a challenge and for that reason, this type of contributions will be specially considered in this conference .\r This conference is the forum in which to present the application of innovative techniques to complex problems.\r The scope of this conference has been kept wide and following are the topics covered (But not limited to):\r A) COMPUTING\r  Autonomic, adaptive, dependable computing, Quantum computing, Parallel computing, Distributed computing, Services computing and cloud computing, Fog and edge computing, Osmotic Computing, Green computing, High performance computing, Graphics and Immersive computing, Pervasive computing, Internet computing, Scientific computing, Business process computing, Spatial computing, Supercomputing systems, Software evolution and mining, Architectural concepts for systems, Network science, social networks, collective intelligence\r B) COMMUNICATION\r  Emerging technologies for next generation network, LAN/WAN/MAN, Future Internet architecture, protocols and services, Content- and service-centric architecture, Mobile and ubiquitous networks, Self organizing/autonomic networking, Green networking, Internet content search, QoS and multimedia networking, Opportunistic networking, On-line social networks, Internet of things, Public safety communication networks, Network applications (web, multimedia streaming, VoIP, gaming, etc.), Trust, security and privacy in computer and communication networks, Modeling, measurement and simulation, Complex network models, Internet socio-economic models, Experimental test-beds and research platforms, Algorithmic aspects of communication networks, Network scaling and limits\r C) LEARNING (PROBLEMS & METHODS)\r I) Learning Problems: Classification, Regression, Recognition, and prediction, Problem solving and planning, Reasoning and inference, Data mining, Web mining, Information retrieval, Natural language processing, Design and diagnosis, Vision and speech perception, Robotics and control, Combinatorial optimization, Game playing, Industrial, financial, and scientific applications of all kinds\r II) Learning Methods: Supervised and unsupervised learning methods, Reinforcement learning, Evolution-based methods, Explanation-based learning, Analogical learning methods, Automated knowledge acquisition, Learning from instruction, Visualization of patterns in data, Learning in integrated architectures, Multistrategy learning, Multi-agent learning\r Paper Submission Link: https://easychair.org/conferences/?conf=cocole2022\r Important Dates: \r Last Date of Submission: 30-06-2022\r Notification of Acceptance: 30-08-2022\r Last Date of Registration: 05-09-2022\r Camera Ready Submission: 05-09-2022\r Conference Dates: Sep 29 - Oct 01, 2022\r Proceedings: It is planned to publish the proceedings with Springer in their Communications in Computer and Information Science series (final approval pending).\r Contact:\r Dr. Sanjaya Kumar Panda, Dept. of CSE, NIT Warangal, Telangana, INDIA\r Mobile: +91-98611 26947\r Email: sanjaya@nitw.ac.in, sanjayauce@gmail.com\n\t"

Call For Papers: b'\nHybrid ANNPR 2022: due to the status of the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic, remote presentations and attendance will be accommodated. Nonetheless, ANNPR 2022 is being planned as an in-presence event, and we encourage perspective attendees to join us in Dubai.\r *** Deadline extension\r 10th IAPR TC3 International Workshop on Artificial Neural Networks in Pattern Recognition (ANNPR 2022)\r              November 24th - 26th, 2022\r              Dubai Campus of Heriot-Watt University, Dubai, UAE\r\t      URL:  https://annpr2022.com/\rSponsored by the International Association for Pattern Recognition (IAPR)\r *** The submission deadline is extended to July 3rd, 2022 ***\r New Important Dates\r   Paper submission (extended):\t   July 3, 2022\r   Notification of acceptance:     Jul 29, 2022\r   Camera ready due:               Sep  4, 2022\r   Early registration:\t\t   Sep  4, 2022\r   Workshop:                       Nov. 24-26, 2022 (Thu to Sat)\r The Workshop proceedings will be published in the Springer LNAI series\r ANNPR 2022 invites papers that present original work in the areas of neural networks and machine learning oriented to pattern recognition, focusing on their algorithmic, theoretical, and applied aspects. Topics of interest include, but are not limited to:\r    Methodological Issues\r     - Supervised, semi-supervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement learning\r     - Deep learning and deep reinforcement learning\r     - Feed-forward, recurrent, and convolutional neural networks\r     - Hierarchical modular architectures and hybrid systems\r     - Interpretability and explainability of neural networks\r     - Generative models\r     - Robustness & generalization of neural networks\r     - Meta-learning, Auto-ML\r     - Multiple classifier systems and ensemble methods\r     - Kernel machines\r     - Probabilistic graphical models\r    Applications to Pattern Recognition\r     - Image processing and segmentation\r     - Object detection\r     - NLP and conversational agents\r     - Sensor-fusion and multi-modal processing\r     - Biometrics, including sspeech and speaker recognition and segmentation\r     - Data, text, and social media analytics\r     - Bioinformatics/Cheminformatics and medical applications\r     - Industrial applications, e.g. quality control and predictive maintenance\r     - Data clustering\r ANNPR 2022 is organized by the Technical Committee 3 (IAPR TC3) on Neural Networks & Computational Intelligence of the International Association for Pattern Recognition (IAPR). As such, we particularly encourage submissions that fit the Manifesto and the research directions of the TC3 (see http://iapr-tc3.diism.unisi.it/Research.html). The maximum paper length is 12 pages. Submission of a paper constitutes a commitment that, if accepted, at least one of the Authors will complete an early registration to the workshop. On-line submission via EasyChair is available through the aforementioned ANNPR 2022 web-page.\r For more information, please visit us at:\rhttps://annpr2022.com/\rDo not hesitate to contact the ANNPR 2022 Chairs for any inquiries.\r ANNPR 2022 Chairs:\rNeamat El Gayar, Heriot-Watt University, Dubai (UAE)\rHazem Abbas, Ain Shams University, Cairo (Egypt)\rMirco Ravanelli, Concordia University, Montr\xc3\xa9al (Canada)\rEdmondo Trentin, University of Siena, Siena (Italy)\r\n'

title: b'MLE 2022'
description: b'4th International Workshop on Modeling Language Engineering (MLE)'
Categories: b'domain-specific languages' b'software language engineering' b'model-driven engineering' b'software engineering'
Call For Papers: b'\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------\rCall for Papers:\r4th International Workshop on Modeling Language Engineering (MLE)\rco-located with MODELS 2022,\r23-25 October, 2022,\rMontr\xc3\xa9al, Canada\rhttps://mleworkshop.github.io/editions/mle2022\r-----------------------------------------------------------------------\r  ---------------------------\rAbout the conference\r---------------------------\r  Software-intensive systems are complicated, driven by the need to integrate across multiple concerns. Consequently, the development of such systems requires the integration of different concerns and skills. These concerns can be covered by different domain-specific modeling languages, with specific concepts, technologies, and abstraction levels. This multiplication of languages eases the development related to each individual specific concern but raises language and technology integration problems at the different stages of the software life cycle. To reason about the global system as a whole, it is necessary to explicitly describe the different kinds of relationships that exist between the different languages used in its development. To support effective language integration, there is a pressing need to reify and classify these relationships, as well as the language interactions that the relationships enable. Equally, the proliferation of domain-specific modeling languages required increases the need for effective and efficient techniques for engineering languages and their support infrastructures (transformations, analysis tools, editors, execution infrastructure, debuggers, \xe2\x80\xa6).\r The Modeling Language Engineering (MLE) workshop aims at bringing together researchers and practitioners working on modeling-language and software-language engineering. It is a meeting opportunity for Software Language Engineering (SLE) enthusiasts within the software-modeling community.\r ---------------------------\rTopics\r---------------------------\r The topics of interest for MLE 2022 include:\r  - Methodologies, languages, techniques, and methods for designing and implementing modeling languages\r- Composition, extension, and reuse of modeling languages and model execution tools\r- Heterogeneous modeling, simulation, and execution\r- Customization of modeling languages\r- Integration of modeling languages and programming languages\r- Semantics-aware model transformations and code generation\r- Scalability of model execution and execution-based model analysis\r- Execution of partial and underspecified models\r- Model execution in the presence of non-determinism and concurrency\r- Tracing model executions and analyzing model execution traces\r- Model execution tools for the (dynamic) validation, verification, and testing of systems (e.g., model animation, debugging, simulation, trace exploration, model checking, symbolic execution)\r- Live modeling and exploratory modeling techniques\r- Automation techniques for the development of modeling and model execution tools\r- Evolution in the context of executable modeling (e.g.} evolution of executable modeling languages, execution semantics, executable models, model execution tools)\r- Verification of semantic conformance (e.g., among executable modeling languages, executable models, model execution tools)\r- Integration challenges for languages, from requirements to design, for analysis and simulation, during runtime, etc.\r- Case studies and experience reports on the successful or failed adoption of modeling in different application domains and application contexts\r- Surveys and benchmarks of different approaches for the development of modeling languages, model execution, and execution-based model analysis\r Submissions describing practical and industrial experience related to the use of modeling languages are also encouraged, particularly in the following application domains:\rCyber-Physical Systems, Smart Manufacturing, Industry 4.0;  Internet of Services, Internet of Things; Smart City, Smart Building, Home automation; Smart and Learning systems.\r ---------------------------\rWorkshop Format\r---------------------------\r This full-day workshop will prioritize discussions over presentations. We plan to open with a keynote in the morning, followed by paper presentations. The afternoon will then be spent primarily in discussions inspired by topics raised by the keynotes and paper presentations.  Where there is sufficient divergence in the topics raised, we will create break-out groups of participants interested in each sub-topic. The goal of these discussions is to identify commonalities and connections between different topics, support research networking, cross-pollination, and informal knowledge transfer. The final session of the workshop will be focused on summarising the key topics and ideas discussed at the workshop to help identify the next steps that may be followed up by workshop participants.\r  ---------------------------\rSubmission and Publication\r---------------------------\r We expect early research results about the aforementioned topics, descriptions of problems, case studies, experience reports, or solutions related to the topics of interest.\r Each contribution must be described in a short paper of 5 pages or a full paper of 10 pages, in ACM format (acmart). Two more pages containing only references are permitted.\r Papers that describe use cases or novel approaches can be accompanied by concrete artifacts, such as models (requirements, design, analysis, transformation, composition, etc.), stored in a public repository. Artifacts should illustrate any experience with the conjoint use of different modeling languages.\r All submissions have to follow the ACM format (acmart) and must be submitted electronically in PDF format [via Easychair](https://easychair.org/my/conference?conf=mle2022). They will be evaluated by at least three members of the program committee regarding novelty, correctness, significance, readability, and alignment with the workshop call. Furthermore, all submissions must be original work and must not have been previously published or being under review elsewhere. The accepted papers will be included in the joint workshop proceedings published in the ACM Digital Library and indexed in DBLP and Scopus.\r   ---------------------------\rImportant Dates\r---------------------------\r - Abstract submission deadline: July 13, 2022\r- Paper submission deadline: July 20, 2022\r- Notification of acceptance: August 19, 2022\r- Camera-ready deadline: August 26, 2022\r  ---------------------------\rOrganization committee\r---------------------------\r  - Erwan Bousse (Nantes University)\r- Faezeh Khorram (IMT Atlantique)\r- Juha-Pekka Tolvanen (MetaCase)\r  ---------------------------\rProgram Committee\r---------------------------\r TBA\n\t'

title: b'WPES 2022'
description: b'Workshop on Privacy in the Electronic Society'
Categories: b'privacy' b'anonymity' b'computer security'
Call For Papers: b"\nThe need for privacy-aware policies, regulations, and techniques has been widely recognized. This workshop discusses the problems of privacy in the global interconnected societies and possible solutions. The 2022 Workshop, held in conjunction with the ACM CCS conference, is the twenty-first in a yearly forum for papers on all the different aspects of privacy in today's electronic society.\r The workshop seeks submissions from academia, industry, and government presenting novel research on all theoretical and practical aspects of electronic privacy, as well as experimental studies of fielded systems. We encourage submissions from other communities such as law and business that present these communities' perspectives on technological issues. Topics of interest include, but are not limited to:\r - access and query privacy\r- anonymization and transparency\r- crowdsourcing for privacy and security\r- data correlation and leakage attacks\r- data and computations integrity in emerging scenarios\r- electronic communication privacy\r- electronic communication privacy\r- information dissemination control\r- insider-threat protection\r- models, languages, and techniques for big data protection\r- anonymization of text, unstructured data and multimedia\r- anonymization of longitudinal data and streams\r- statistical disclosure control\r- theory of data anonymization\r- privacy models\r- network privacy\r- personally identifiable information\r- privacy-aware access control\r- privacy and anonymity on the Web\r- privacy in big data\r- privacy in biometric systems\r- privacy in cloud and grid systems\r- privacy and data mining\r- privacy in the digital business\r- privacy in the Internet of Things\r- privacy enhancing technologies\r- privacy in health care and public administration\r- privacy and human rights\r- privacy metrics\r- privacy in mobile systems\r- privacy in outsourced scenarios\r- privacy in sensor networks\r- privacy in surveillance systems\r- privacy policies\r- privacy of provenance data\r- privacy in social networks\r- privacy threats\r- privacy and virtual identity\r- user privacy\r- wireless privacy\r  ------------------------\rSUBMISSION INSTRUCTIONS\r------------------------\rSubmitted papers must not substantially overlap papers that have been published or that are simultaneously submitted to a journal or a conference with proceedings. Submissions should be no more than 12 pages in the ACM double-column format, excluding the bibliography and well-marked appendix. Committee members are not required to read the appendices, and so the paper should be intelligible without them. Submissions should not be anonymized. The workshop will also consider short submissions of up to 4 pages for results that are preliminary or that simply require few pages to describe. Authors of regular submitted papers will indicate at the time of submission whether they would like their paper to also be considered for publication as a short paper (4 proceedings pages).\r Submissions are to be made to the submission website at EasyChair. Only PDF files will be accepted. Submissions not meeting these guidelines risk rejection without consideration of their merits. Papers must be received by the deadline of July 16, 2022 (11:59 PM American Samoa time) to be considered. Notification of acceptance or rejection will be sent to authors by August 31, 2022.\r Authors of accepted papers must guarantee that their paper will be presented at the workshop.\n\t"

Call For Papers: b'\nInternational Workshop on Runtime and Operating Systems for Supercomputers\r                           ***  ROSS 2022  ***\r Held in conjunction with SC22: The International Conference for High\rPerformance Computing, Networking, Storage and Analysis,\rDallas, Texas, USA, November 13, 2022\r ==========================================================================\r                  https://events.cels.anl.gov/ross/2022/\r==========================================================================\r The complexity of node architectures in supercomputers increases as we\rcross milestones on the way towards Exascale and beyond. Increasing levels\rof parallelism in multi- and many-core chips and emerging heterogeneity of\rcomputational resources coupled with energy and memory constraints force a\rreevaluation of our approaches towards operating systems and runtime\renvironments.\r The ROSS workshop, to be held as a half-day event in conjunction with the\rSC22 conference, focuses on principles and techniques to design,\rimplement, optimize, or operate runtime and operating systems for\rmassively parallel supercomputers and cloud environments for\rhigh-performance computing.\r In addition to typical workshop publications, we encourage novel and\rpossibly immature ideas, provided that they are interesting and on-topic.\rWell argued position papers are also welcome.\r  TOPICS OF INTEREST:\r-------------------\r - OS and runtime system scalability on many-node and multi/many-core systems\r- management of heterogeneous and reconfigurable compute resources, including FPGAs, GPUs, etc.\r- distributed/hybrid/partitioned OSes and runtime systems for Supercomputing\r- system noise analysis and prevention\r- runtime and operating systems for resource disaggregation\r- modeling and performance analysis of runtime systems\r- the use of machine learning and AI techniques in the autotuning of system software\r- OS and runtime considerations for large-volume, high-performance I/O\r- memory management and emerging memory technologies\r- OS and runtime aspects of HPC in the cloud, convergence of Supercomputing and cloud environments\r- infrastructure for cloud functions and serverless computing in the context of HPC\r- virtualization in HPC, including virtual machines and application containers\r- the role of OS and runtime system in minimizing power usage\r SUBMISSION PROCEDURE:\r----------------------------------\r The ROSS workshop proceedings will be published electronically via the IEEE\rComputer Society Digital Library.  Submitted manuscripts should be\rformatted using the IEEE template conference mode.  The maximum paper\rlength is 8 pages, not including references and other appendices.  All\rpapers must be in English. Please visit the workshop website for further\rinstructions and the submission link.\r WORKSHOP CHAIRS:\r----------------\r Balazs Gerofi        RIKEN, Japan\rTorsten Hoefler      ETH Zurich, Switzerland\rKamil Iskra          Argonne National Laboratory, USA\r PROGRAM COMMITTEE:\r------------------\r Patrick Bridges, University of New Mexico, USA\rBronis R. de Supinski, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, USA\rMaya Gokhale, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, USA\rKyle Hale, Illinois Institute of Technology, USA\rJohn Lange, Oak Ridge National Laboratory and University of Pittsburgh, USA\rBernd Mohr, Juelich Supercomputing Centre, Germany\rYoonho Park, IBM Research, USA\rKevin Pedretti, Sandia National Laboratories, USA\rMiquel Pericas, Chalmers University of Technology, Sweden\rRolf Riesen, Intel, USA\rCarsten Weinhold, Barkhausen Institute, Germany\r Contact us at sc-ws-ross@info.supercomputing.org if you have any questions.\n\t'

Call For Papers: b'\nCall for submissions for \rThe ALP Alain Colmerauer Prolog Heritage Prize\rto be presented at the Prolog Day Symposium\r Organized by The Association for Logic Programming (ALP) and The Prolog \rHeritage Association\r In the  summer of  1972, Alain  Colmerauer and  his team  in Marseille\rdeveloped and implemented  the first version of  the logic programming\rlanguage Prolog.  Together with both earlier  and later collaborations\rwith Robert Kowalski  and his colleagues in Edinburgh,  this work laid\rthe practical  and theoretical  foundations for  the Prolog  and logic\rprogramming of today. Prolog and  its related technologies soon became\rkey tools of symbolic programming and Artificial Intelligence.\r The Year of Prolog celebrates the 50th anniversary of these events and\rhighlights the continuing significance of Prolog and Logic Programming\rboth for symbolic, explainable AI, and for computing more generally.\r This  celebration  will culminate  with  the  award of  the  inaugural\redition of the  ALP Alain Colmerauer Prolog Heritage  Prize for recent\rpractical   accomplishments    that   highlight   the    benefits   of\rProlog-inspired computing for the future.  The Prize will be presented\rat the Prolog Day Symposium on November 10, 2022, in Paris, France.\r Eligibility\r-----------\rAny  individual or  group of  individuals can  nominate themselves  or\rtheir institution(s)/organization(s) for the Prize.\r Selection\r---------\rThe Prize  will be given for  depth, novelty, and proven  or potential\rimpact. A shortlist of up to five nominations will also be selected in\rthe process.\r Endowment\r---------\rThe winner(s)  will receive a  certificate and  a cash Prize  of 2,000\rEuros.  The expenses of the shortlisted nominees will be covered up to\r1,000 Euros, supported by the Artificial Intelligence Journal.\r Timeline\r--------\rDeadline for nominations/submissions:\r*** September 2, 2022 ***\r Notification of the shortlisted candidates:\r*** September 30, 2022 ***\r For more information and details, see:\rhttps://prologyear.logicprogramming.org/ColmerauerPrize.html\r ----------------------------------------------------------------------\rThe Year of Prolog and  its activities, including the Alain Colmerauer\rPrize, are  sponsored by  the Association  for Logic  Programming, the\rProlog  Heritage   Association,  the   AI  Journal,   Institut  Carnot\rCognition, and Institut Fredrik Bull, among others.\n\t'

title: b'WoSAR 2022'
description: b'14th International Workshop on Software Aging and Rejuvenation'
Categories: b'software aging' b'software rejuvenation'
Call For Papers: b'\nSoftware aging is a problem of progressive degradation of performance and dependability in computer pro-grams, especially those executing for long period of time. This phenomenon has been extensively studied for more than 20 years, as it affects many systems, from embedded devices to server software to critical systems. \r Software rejuvenation, i.e., proactive restart of applications (components/threads/tasks), reboot of VMs or machines, and failover to a replica are the most prominent approach es to combat software aging. A variety of rejuvenation techniques, scheduling plans, scopes and granularities, have been proposed for different applica-tion types and platforms. \r WoSAR is the premier international venue to discuss the recent advances and discoveries in theoretical and practical aspects of software aging and rejuvenation research. In this year, we encourage submissions targeting interdisciplinary research, in particular those listed in the topics of interest.\r TOPICS OF INTEREST\r This call for papers addresses all researchers and practitioners with an interest about performance and depend-ability degradation of software systems. Topics addressed in the workshop include but are not limited to:\r \xc2\xb7\tProgressive degradation of performability / availability / reliability / scalability / \xe2\x80\x9c-ilities\xe2\x80\x9d in software sys-tems.\r\xc2\xb7\tOn-line feedback control view of software rejuvenation.\r\xc2\xb7\tModeling and characterization of the software aging phenomenon.\r\xc2\xb7\tDesign and evaluation of rejuvenation techniques.\r\xc2\xb7\tAnalysis of aging-related faults/bugs, errors, and failures.\r\xc2\xb7\tSoftware test strategies for detecting aging-related bugs.\r\xc2\xb7\tMonitoring, detection and data analysis of software aging effects (e.g., memory leaks, database index frag-mentation, unterminated processes/threads, accrual of round-off errors). \r\xc2\xb7\tNew classes of software aging effects.\r\xc2\xb7\tSoftware aging and rejuvenation applied to anomaly detection and security intrusions.\r\xc2\xb7\tSoftware aging and rejuvenation in Big Data and IoT Apps.\r\xc2\xb7\tPrognostics and Health Management (PHM) interactions with software aging and rejuvenation approaches.\r\xc2\xb7\tEnvironment-dependent bugs and their mitigation techniques.\r\xc2\xb7\tMetrics for software performance and degradation.\r\xc2\xb7\tFault localization and testing for aging-related bugs.\r\xc2\xb7\tSoftware refactoring for aging-related software problems.\r\xc2\xb7\tClone detection in aging software.\r\xc2\xb7\tMachine learning techniques for aging-related bugs.\r\xc2\xb7\tTools for detection and repair of memory leaks.\r\xc2\xb7\tSoftware aging monitoring and software rejuvenation techniques for unmanned vehicles like drones or cars.\r\xc2\xb7\tSoftware aging and rejuvenation techniques for humans in safety-critical environments, like large ware-houses.\r\xc2\xb7\tOther software-aging-related phenomena, such as age of information.\r\xc2\xb7\tAnalytical, empirical, and experimental studies of any of the above topics.\r For all the above topics, WoSAR is a unique forum to discuss the software aging and rejuvenation impacts on systems from different domains of applicability such as: \rCloud computing, Mobile Edge Computing, Fog computing, Mobile, Machine learning systems, Embedded, Medical, Cyber-physical systems, Cyber-Security, Industrial control systems such as SCADA, Smart Grids, Smart Infrastructures, Smart Cities, Transportation, Telecommunication, Military, System of systems, Data-bases, High Performance Computing, Software Defined Networks, and others.\r  IMPORTANT DATES\rPaper submission deadline: August 1, 2022\rPaper notification: August 19, 2022\rCamera-ready papers: August 26, 2022\r  RESEARCH PAPER SUBMISSION\rAuthors are invited to submit high quality unpublished  work describing the results of theoretical and experi-mental software aging and rejuvenation research. All the accepted papers will be included in the IEEE Xplore Digital Library.\rPapers must be written in English and be formatted according to the IEEE authoring guidelines . Full papers should not exceed seven pages in IEEE style. Paper submission will be done electronically through EasyChair .\r  SPECIAL SESSION ON INVITED JOURNAL PAPERS \rThere will be a special session titled \xe2\x80\x9cInvited Journal Papers\xe2\x80\x9d at WoSAR 2022. During this session, researchers will have the opportunity to present any of their recently published peer-reviewed journal articles. title: b'CoCo4MT 2022'
description: b'The First Workshop on Corpus Generation and Corpus Augmentation for Machine Translation'
Categories: b'machine translation' b'natural language processing' b'linguistics' b'corpora'
Call For Papers: b'\nThe First Workshop on Corpus Generation and Corpus Augmentation for Machine Translation (CoCo4MT)\rhttps://sites.google.com/view/coco4mt\r@ AMTA \xe2\x80\x93 2022\rThis 15th biennial conference of the Association for Machine Translation in the Americas \r12-16 September 2022, Orlando, Florida, USA\r INVITED TALKS\r Julia Kreutzer Google Research\rMore TBA...\r SCOPE\r It is a well-known fact that machine translation systems, especially those that use deep learning, require massive amounts of data. Several resources for languages are not available in their human-created format. Some of the types of resources available are monolingual, multilingual, translation memories, and lexicons. Those types of resources are generally created for formal purposes such as parliamentary collections when parallel and more informal situations when monolingual. The quality and abundance of resources including corpora used for formal reasons is generally higher than those used for informal purposes. Additionally, corpora for low-resource languages, languages with less digital resources available, tends to be less abundant and of lower quality.\r CoCo4MT sets out to be the first workshop centered around research that focuses on corpora creation, cleansing, and augmentation techniques specifically for machine translation. We accept work that covers any spoken language (including high-resource languages) but we are specifically interested in those submissions that are on languages with limited existing resources (low-resource languages) where resources are not highly available. \r The goal of this workshop is to begin to close the gap between corpora available for low-resource translation systems and promote high-quality data for online systems that can be used by native speakers of low-resource languages is of particular interest. Therefore, It will be beneficial if the techniques presented in research papers include their impact on the quality of MT output and how they can be used in the real world.\r CoCo4MT aims to encourage research on new and undiscovered techniques. We hope that submissions will provide high-quality corpora that is available publicly for download and can be used to increase machine translation performance thus encouraging new dataset creation for multiple languages that will, in turn, provide a general workshop to consult for corpora needs in the future. The workshop\xe2\x80\x99s success will be measured by the following key performance indicators:\r - Promotes the ongoing increase in quality of machine translation systems when measured by standard measurements,\r- Provides a meeting place for collaboration from several research areas to increase the availability of commonly used corpora and new corpora,\r- Drives innovation to address the need for higher quality and abundance of low-resource language data.\r TOPICS\r We are highly interested in original research papers  on the topics below; however, we welcome all novel ideas that cover research on corpora techniques.\r - Difficulties with using existing corpora (e.g., political considerations or domain limitations) and their effects on final MT systems,\r- Strategies for collecting new MT datasets (e.g., via crowdsourcing),\r- Data augmentation techniques,\r- Data cleansing and denoising techniques, \r- Quality control strategies for MT data,\r- Exploration of datasets for pretraining or auxiliary tasks for training MT systems.\r SUBMISSION INFORMATION\r There is one type of submission in the workshop:  Research, review and position paper. The length of each paper should be at least four (4) and not exceed ten (10) pages, plus unlimited pages for references. Submissions should be formatted according to the official AMTA 2022 style templates (PDF, LaTeX, Word). Accepted papers will be published on-line in the AMTA 2022 proceedings which includes the ACL Anthology and will be presented at the conference either orally or as a poster. \r Submissions must be anonymized and should be done using the official conference management system (https://cmt3.research.microsoft.com/AMTA2022). Scientific papers that have been or will be submitted to other venues must be declared as such, and must be withdrawn from the other venues if accepted and published at CoCo4MT. The review will be double-blind. \r We would like to encourage authors to cite papers written in ANY language that are related to the topics, as long as both original bibliographic items and their corresponding English translations are provided.\r Registration will be handled by the main conference. (To be announced)\r IMPORTANT DATES\r June 1, 2022 \xe2\x80\x93 Call for papers released\rJune 15, 2022 \xe2\x80\x93 Second call for papers\rJuly 29, 2022 \xe2\x80\x93 Third and final call for papers\rJuly 13, 2022 \xe2\x80\x93 Paper submissions due\rJuly 27, 2022 \xe2\x80\x93 Notification of acceptance\rAugust 7, 2022 \xe2\x80\x93  Camera-ready due\rAugust 31, 2022 \xe2\x80\x93  Video recordings due\rSeptember 16, 2022 - CoCo4MT workshop\r CONTACT\r CoCo4MT Workshop Organizers\rcoco4mt2022@googlegroups.com\r ORGANIZING COMMITTEE (listed alphabetically)\r Constantine Lignos     Brandeis University\rJohn E. Call For Papers: b'\nCall-for-Papers\rIP&MC2022 Interdisciplinary-topics (VSI: IPMC2022 INTERDISCIPLINE)\r A Special Issue for Information Processing & Management (IP&M), Elsevier\r Note: This special issue is a Thematic Track at IP&MC2022. For more information about IP&MC2022, please visit https://www.elsevier.com/events/conferences/information-processing-and-management-conference.\rTitle of the Special Issue\r IP&MC2022 INTERDISCIPLINARY-TOPICS (VSI: IPMC2022 INTERDISCIPLINE)\rGuest Editors\r Name:Yanwu Yang (Managing Guest Editor)\r University: Huazhong University of Science and Technology\r Email: yangyanwu@hust.edu.cn\r Name: Chunjie Zhang\r University: Beijing Jiaotong University\r Email: cjzhang@bjtu.edu.cn\r Name: Kang Zhao\rUniversity: The University of Iowa\r Email: kang-zhao@uiowa.edu\r Name: Qian Wang\r University: Sun Yat-sen University\r Email: mnswq@mail.sysu.edu.cn\r Name: Christophe Claramunt\r University: Naval Academy Research Institute\r Email: christophe.claramunt@gmail.com\r Background\r This track at IP&MC2022 and a special issue in Information Processing and Management will publish cutting-edge original research at the intersection of information science, computing, artificial intelligence, economics, and social science concerning theory, methods, or applications in a range of domains, including but not limited to information science, information technology, management, advertising and marketing, energy, health, economics and social computing, and metaverse.\r The track aims to serve the interests of primary researchers but also practitioners in furthering knowledge at the intersection of information science, computing, artificial intelligence, and social science by providing an effective forum for the timely dissemination of advanced and topical issues. The track is especially interested in original research articles, research survey articles, research method articles, and articles addressing critical applications of research.\r Specifically, the track is interested in four types of manuscripts, which are:\r Research manuscripts addressing topics at the intersection of information science, computing, artificial intelligence, and social science.\rMethods manuscripts focusing on applying novel methods at the intersection of information science, computing, artificial intelligence and social science.\rReview manuscripts assessing, in a critical and in-depth manner, a broad trend at the intersection of information science, computing, artificial intelligence, and social science, providing integration of the prior research, and recommendations for further work in the area.\rCritical application manuscripts concerning system design research at the intersection of information science, computing, artificial intelligence, and social science.\r We invite authors to submit their research work (including full-length, original, and unpublished research papers based on theoretical or experimental contributions and review studies), especially in areas of information science, information technology, management, advertising and marketing, energy, health, economics and social computing, and metaverse.\rPossible Topics of Submissions\r Topics of interest include, but are not limited to:\r creation and analysis of evaluation methodologies for interdisciplinary topics of informatics, computing, statistical learning, artificial intelligence, and metaverse technologies in a range of application domains;\rdimensions of the relationship between information, technology, and contextual changes;\rimplications and impacts of informatics, computing, statistical learning, artificial intelligence, and metaverse technologies;\rmodels or algorithms with solid empirical validation of informatics, computing, statistical learning, artificial intelligence, and metaverse;\rinsights on the strengths and weaknesses of informatics, computing, statistical learning, artificial intelligence, and metaverse technologies;\rrelationships between theory, policy, and practice of informatics, computing, statistical learning, artificial intelligence, and metaverse technologies;\rrigorous work of an empirical, experimental, or ethnographic nature in the fields of informatics, computing, statistical learning, artificial intelligence, and metaverse;\ruser studies yielding new insights into informatics, computing, statistical learning, artificial intelligence, and metaverse technologies;\rliterature surveys of existing work that propose a significant synthesis in informatics, computing, statistical learning, artificial intelligence, and metaverse;\rthe individual and the social, the cultural and the political dimensions of informatics, computing, statistical learning, artificial intelligence, and metaverse technologies.\r Important Dates\rOnline submission system is open January 5, 2022\rThematic track manuscript submission due date; authors are welcome to submit early as reviews will be rolling June 15, 2022\rAuthor notification July 31, 2022\rIP&MC conference presentation and feedback October 20-23, 2022\rPost conference revision due date, but authors welcome to submit earlier title: b'MULTIMODALITY 2022'

Categories: b'linguistic' b'multimodality' b'language'
Call For Papers: b'\nEntrepalavras (Quailis CAPES B1-2016), a peer-reviewed journal dedicated to Linguistics (Federal University of Ceara-Brazil), invites researchers to submit their paper to its special issue \xe2\x80\x9cMultimodality in social practices\xe2\x80\x9d. More details can be found below and on the journal\xe2\x80\x99s website (www.entrepalavras.ufc.br/revista). There is no charge for submission and publication fees. \r Guest Editors: Dr. Paulo Gon\xc3\xa7alves Segundo (USP); Dr Rosalice Pinto (Universidade Nova de Lisboa) and  Dr. Isabel Muniz (UFAL).\r Theme: Multimodality in social practices\r There is a consensus that the use of multisemiosis, according to different theoretical approaches (KRESS and van LEEUWEN, 2006; ELIAS, 2016; CARVALHO, 2020; MACAGNO and PINTO, 2021), in many human activities, has been occupying an increasingly important place in the various researches related to such theme, as well as in the various professional and social practices in which it is found. In fact, this can get even more complex in regards to the new challenges imposed by new digital technologies and the different ways of interacting. In this context, textual-discursive aspects can come to materialize, assuming great relevance. Thus, considering the relevance of this topic in the current studies of Language Sciences, Entrepalavras invites researchers, scholars, and professors to submit unpublished contributions in the various areas of language studies and other related areas of knowledge, to be published on its thematic issue: Multimodality in Social Practices. This issue aims to disseminate articles and research that focus on the various textual-discursive studies dealing with multimodality in its various social manifestations.\r Timetable: \r Submission deadline: August 31, 2022. \r Publication: December, 2022. \n\t'
